# Deobfuscated Code Analysis

## Deobfuscated Version

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π (full circle in radians)
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics simulation parameters
var config = {
    attractionStrength: 4000,   // Repulsion force between nodes
    springCoeff: 0.004,         // Spring stiffness for edges
    amplification: 0.92,        // Velocity damping (friction)
    gravityStrength: 0.0003,    // Pull toward center
    maxParticles: 40,           // Max stream particles
    streamDecay: 0.04,          // Particle speed decay
    theta: 0.06                 // Camera smoothing factor
};

// ===== NODES =====
var nodes = [
    { id: 'hub',      label: 'Hub',      r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Alpha',    r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',     r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',    r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',    r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon',  r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// ===== EDGES (springs connecting nodes) =====
var edges = [
    { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// Particle stream
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
    }
    return null;
}

// Main physics step
function updatePhysics() {
    // 1. Node-to-node REPULSION (Coulomb-like force)
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
            var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
            var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
            var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
            var force = config.attractionStrength / (dist * dist);
            var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
            var fy = (dy / dist) * force;

            nodes[i].vx += fx;
            nodes[i].vy += fy;
            nodes[j].vx -= fx;
            nodes[j].vy -= fy;
        }
    }

    // 2. SPRING forces along edges (Hooke's law)
    for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
        var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
        var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
        if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;

        var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
        var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
        var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
        var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
        var force = (edges[e].k || config.springCoeff) * displacement;

        nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
    }

    // 3. Apply gravity toward center, damping, and position update
    for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
        // Gravity pull toward center (400, 300)
        nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.gravityStrength;
        nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.gravityStrength;

        // Velocity damping (friction)
        nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
        nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;

        // Update positions
        nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
        nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
    }
}

// Spawn a decorative particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
    if (particles.length >= config.maxParticles) return;

    var sourceNode = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
    var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
    var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

    particles.push({
        x: sourceNode.x,
        y: sourceNode.y,
        vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
        vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
        age: 0,
        maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
        size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
    });
}

// Update all particles
function updateParticles() {
    for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        var p = particles[i];
        p.age++;

        // Remove expired particles
        if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
            particles.splice(i, 1);
            continue;
        }

        // Apply decay to velocity
        p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
        p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);

        // Update position
        p.x += p.vx;
        p.y += p.vy;
    }
}

// Smooth camera follow
function updateCamera() {
    camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
    camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
    camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}

// Main loop tick
function tick() {
    updatePhysics();
    updateParticles();
    updateCamera();

    // Spawn a particle every 3rd frame
    if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
    frameCount++;
}

// Run at ~60fps (16ms interval)
setInterval(tick, 16);
```

## What It Does

This is a **force-directed graph simulation** — the physics engine behind a network visualization. Here's the breakdown:

### 🔵 Graph Structure
- **6 nodes** (Hub, Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon) connected by **8 edges** forming a hub-and-spoke network
- The **Hub** is the central, largest node

### ⚡ Physics Engine (3 forces per tick)
| Force | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| **Repulsion** | All nodes push each other apart (inverse-square law, like electric charges) |
| **Springs** | Connected nodes are pulled together toward a rest length (Hooke's law) |
| **Gravity** | All nodes drift toward center point (400, 300) to prevent flying off |

Velocity **damping** (0.92× per frame) acts as friction so the system eventually stabilizes.

### ✨ Particle Effects
Every 3 frames, a decorative particle spawns from a random node, drifts outward with slowly decaying velocity, and dies after 800–2000 frames. Max 40 particles at once.

### 🎥 Camera
A smooth-follow camera lerps toward a target position at 6% per frame.

### ⏱️ Execution
`setInterval` runs the simulation at **~60 FPS** (16ms). This is **purely the simulation logic** — there's no rendering code here, suggesting a separate draw loop reads the node/particle positions to render them (likely on an HTML Canvas).

> **In short:** This is the backend physics for an animated, force-directed network graph with floating particles — commonly seen in data visualization dashboards or interactive node maps.
